where we can see that some
of the content is being pushed up

00:18:17.340 --> 00:18:19.580
and new content is being displayed.

00:18:19.700 --> 00:18:24.940
Then the second one,
we just see that it has an icon with a title.

00:18:26.580 --> 00:18:28.220
Where to begin on these?

00:18:28.340 --> 00:18:35.780
For one, we have problematic animations
that whenever the user interacts with it,

00:18:35.940 --> 00:18:41.700
they get bombarded with an experience
that they likely didn't sign up for.

00:18:41.860 --> 00:18:50.060
Then we're also hiding
a valuable content underneath this.

00:18:50.180 --> 00:18:53.540
When a user is scanning
through the site,

00:18:53.700 --> 00:18:56.340
these cards aren't clearly clickable.

00:18:56.460 --> 00:19:00.660
There's no indicator
that the user needs to take an action.

00:19:00.780 --> 00:19:05.580
This content is being hidden
from so many users

00:19:05.740 --> 00:19:07.660
that they're not going to be able to see

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:15.780
or get to know what you're trying
to promote for them, and it's frustrating.

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:20.700
Not to mention users with motion sensitivity
and different things like that.

00:19:20.860 --> 00:19:28.140
My recommendation for items
like these is to just go with a static card.

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:31.300
It is fine to put it all out on the table

00:19:31.460 --> 00:19:34.180
and show your users all of the content,

00:19:34.340 --> 00:19:37.780
so having that icon
at the top, the title.

00:19:37.940 --> 00:19:42.660
Then let's put just
the content underneath it so that way,

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:43.660
the user can see it.

00:19:43.860 --> 00:19:48.260
If that card is meant to be clickable,
please add an indicator.

00:19:49.860 --> 00:19:55.380
We just keep on waving
with the animated items.

00:19:55.540 --> 00:20:00.220
This one has to be one
of my least favorites

00:20:00.300 --> 00:20:04.940
on my red flag list
is the animated titles.

00:20:05.420 --> 00:20:09.940
For some reason,
page builders love these,

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:12.220
and I will never figure out the reason why.

00:20:12.380 --> 00:20:18.460
These animated titles are problematic
because they're always changing text.

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:20.460
There's a constant animation.

00:20:20.660 --> 00:20:24.900
They don't allow the user
to pause or play the animations.

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:27.540
It's just [mimics aversion].

00:20:27.660 --> 00:20:30.700
If you need a title or a headline,

00:20:30.820 --> 00:20:35.540
please just use a properly
marked up headline.

00:20:35.660 --> 00:20:37.340
That is perfectly okay.

00:20:39.140 --> 00:20:40.420
Here's an example.

00:20:40.540 --> 00:20:44.220
Again, I wasn't going
to subject you guys to all that movement

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:49.300
and everything going on,
but here's a screenshot of an animated title.

00:20:49.460 --> 00:20:53.860
On the screen,
we see there's just some filler content

00:20:54.020 --> 00:20:56.180
that's flowing off
of the page.

00:20:56.340 --> 00:20:59.660
As I was sitting on the page,
a new word popped in

00:20:59.820 --> 00:21:03.060
and then it went out again
and then another word popped in.

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:04.820
Confusing.

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:09.260
You don't know what message
they're trying to get across to you

00:21:09.380 --> 00:21:12.620
because the content is always changing.

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:18.540
It's bad for users
with motion sensitivity.

00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:23.420
It's tough for anyone
to really keep up with.

00:21:23.540 --> 00:21:25.020
Let's avoid these.

00:21:25.140 --> 00:21:29.220
Let's put these on the page builder
no-no list if we could.

00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:36.260
The animations
just keep on going with these red flags.

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:41.780
Another popular thing
that we see on page builders a lot

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:47.780
is that they'll give you the option
for extra effects and animations,

00:21:47.900 --> 00:21:53.300
such entrance animations and scrolling
animations and different things like that.

00:21:53.460 --> 00:22:00.300
While these aren't always the worst,
they're not the best either.

00:22:00.460 --> 00:22:04.820
They can be used
within a certain realm.

00:22:04.980 --> 00:22:08.820
One thing to note
that I've recently found out

00:22:08.940 --> 00:22:14.500
was that a lot of page builders;
there's a setting within users' browsers

00:22:14.660 --> 00:22:16.460
that they can reduce motion,

00:22:16.620 --> 00:22:21.780
and it's supposed to turn off
the entrance animations and different things.

00:22:21.940 --> 00:22:25.460
There's page builders out there
that are ignoring this,

00:22:25.580 --> 00:22:28.740
which- I mean,
can we say problematic?

00:22:28.900 --> 00:22:34.780
There is some custom code
that you might be able

00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:37.460
to add in there to ensure
that your page builder

00:22:37.580 --> 00:22:40.020
is listening to your users.

00:22:40.100 --> 00:22:44.940
Just ensure you're doing your testing
and everything is looking good.

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:48.300
This is one of those proceed
with great caution

00:22:48.460 --> 00:22:51.900
and ensure
that everything works properly.

00:22:52.060 --> 00:22:57.740
Here's an example that I found
on the Elementor website.

00:22:57.860 --> 00:23:00.540
I guess a big call-out here,
don't come for me,

00:23:00.700 --> 00:23:05.780
but they're using
a scrolling effect to have--

00:23:05.900 --> 00:23:09.860
and they have all these
little cards on top of this headline.

00:23:10.300 --> 00:23:16.660
Then as you scroll, the cards dissipate
and you can then read the headline.

00:23:16.820 --> 00:23:21.100
One, why are we covering up
the headline in the first place?

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:26.540
We're making this a little too difficult
for users to read and interact with.

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:28.740
There's all these cards.

00:23:28.860 --> 00:23:30.660
Are they clickable?

00:23:30.900 --> 00:23:32.540
Am I supposed to do something with it?

00:23:32.700 --> 00:23:33.300
I don't know.

00:23:33.420 --> 00:23:35.700
There's too much.

00:23:35.820 --> 00:23:39.140
It's items like these
that we just need--

00:23:39.260 --> 00:23:43.140
let's toss those out of our options.

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:53.820
Then we're moving,
waving in with our sliders and our carousels.

00:23:53.940 --> 00:24:01.220
Again, we're forcing user interaction
to be able to view our content.

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:04.660
Sliders,
unless they're marked up properly,

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:08.100
don't always work
with assistive technology.

00:24:08.260 --> 00:24:11.780
Usually, within a page builder,
might be a shocker,

00:24:11.900 --> 00:24:14.940
but they're not always
marked up properly.

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:20.260
These are one of the things
that I do recommend avoiding where you can,

00:24:20.380 --> 00:24:22.540
where it is possible.

00:24:22.700 --> 00:24:27.140
The W3C does give us an example

00:24:27.260 --> 00:24:30.500
of what a properly marked up
slider does look like,

00:24:30.620 --> 00:24:36.260
so you at least have that
to go on should you have any questions

00:24:36.380 --> 00:24:39.660
or should you really want
a slider for your website.

00:24:39.780 --> 00:24:41.420
There are ways to make it accessible,

00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:45.060
but I'm never a fan
for hiding content from users.

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:53.500
Here's an example of a slider
that I saw on the Beaver Builder website.

00:24:53.620 --> 00:25:02.860
We see a screenshot of a slider
that has a kitty and a dog playing,

00:25:03.020 --> 00:25:07.180
with an overlay in the center
that has some text and a button.

00:25:07.340 --> 00:25:14.540
Would you believe me if I said
that there's also navigation arrows on this slider?

00:25:15.340 --> 00:25:17.260
No, really, there are.

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:21.740
I just put circles around them on the screen.

00:25:22.260 --> 00:25:25.660
This is also why if you're going to use a slider,

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:31.300
ensuring proper contrast is essential for users.

00:25:31.500 --> 00:25:35.660
Most users
would just come here, see this

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:41.220
and just assume
that it's an image and go on with their way.

00:25:41.310 --> 00:25:43.310
If this is really important content,

00:25:43.600 --> 00:25:48.480
let's put it front
and center for users to find.

00:25:49.150 --> 00:25:53.570
Another thing is ensuring
that your target size is good.

00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:58.740
A lot of sliders love those little
dotted navigations,

00:25:59.030 --> 00:26:01.490
and usually those dots are really tiny.

00:26:01.620 --> 00:26:09.090
Let's enlarge those and make sure
that they're big enough,

00:26:09.840 --> 00:26:15.590
as well as ensuring that sliders have
proper ARIA attributes so that way,

00:26:15.590 --> 00:26:20.310
users on assistive technologies know
what's going on

00:26:20.430 --> 00:26:25.890
and how to get to the content
that you're trying to show them.

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:29.560
All right.

00:26:29.730 --> 00:26:32.940
We are a little bit out of the animation
realm.

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:33.610
Take a breath.

00:26:35.030 --> 00:26:39.120
We are moving more into content-based
items.

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:40.870
Another hydration break here.

00:26:43.120 --> 00:26:46.500
[silence] All right.

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:50.040
First up is accordions and toggles.

00:26:50.920 --> 00:26:54.960
These items are great for being able
to display a lot

00:26:54.960 --> 00:26:57.300
of content in a small area,

00:26:57.720 --> 00:27:01.800
but they can really be problematic
for keyboard users

00:27:01.890 --> 00:27:04.180
and users of assistive technologies.

00:27:04.720 --> 00:27:09.400
A lot of times, I've entered an accordion

00:27:09.400 --> 00:27:13.190
or a toggle on a site built
with a page builder,

00:27:13.190 --> 00:27:16.950
and it just doesn't work with a keyboard.

00:27:18.780 --> 00:27:23.200
You should be able to--
Here on the screen,

00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:26.330
I have a screenshot of an accordion.

00:27:26.700 --> 00:27:32.250
This one was actually taken
from Oxygen Extra's site.

00:27:32.630 --> 00:27:36.300
One of the things that they tout on
there is accessible markup,

00:27:36.380 --> 00:27:40.680
which from what I saw, it was accessible.

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:42.140
They had all the ARIA.

00:27:42.550 --> 00:27:48.270
You should be able to tab on your computer
to the different titles

00:27:48.270 --> 00:27:52.940
within this accordion and then hit enter,
and then you can pop--

00:27:52.940 --> 00:27:55.610
that will pop open
and you can read the content.

00:27:58.150 --> 00:28:00.530
On several page builders out there,

00:28:00.530 --> 00:28:06.540
unfortunately, whenever you tab to it
and you hit enter, it does nothing.

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:10.540
This is why proper markup is so important.

00:28:11.120 --> 00:28:13.330
Whenever we can mark it up properly
to work,

00:28:13.330 --> 00:28:17.630
why would we do it any other way?

00:28:19.220 --> 00:28:20.550
I really don't know.

00:28:22.340 --> 00:28:28.600
Under a similar nature,
waving us in here is tabs.

00:28:29.430 --> 00:28:34.270
In the same way, tabs are also great
for organizing large amounts

00:28:34.270 --> 00:28:38.280
of content while keeping it compact
and easy to understand,

00:28:39.190 --> 00:28:44.950
but these can be problematic
for mobile users, keyboard users,

00:28:45.070 --> 00:28:47.450
and users of assistive technology.

00:28:48.490 --> 00:28:52.920
Again, this is a proceed with caution,
ensuring proper markup.

00:28:53.920 --> 00:28:59.920
The W3C does also have an example
of this of what proper markup looks like.

00:29:00.300 --> 00:29:04.340
If you're curious and then like a tab
on your website,

00:29:04.590 --> 00:29:07.100
that's a great resource to go to.

00:29:07.890 --> 00:29:09.930
I have a couple screenshots here.

00:29:10.270 --> 00:29:15.810
I have one screenshot on this slide
of a tab on desktop.

00:29:16.940 --> 00:29:20.400
If you are a user navigating
via a keyboard,

00:29:20.780 --> 00:29:27.410
you should be able to hit the tab key
and land on the first tab.

00:29:27.700 --> 00:29:30.830
There's three tabs in the screenshot,

00:29:30.830 --> 00:29:33.460
and then we see a simple
content underneath there.

00:29:33.750 --> 00:29:38.840
You would be able to navigate
to the other tabs via your arrow keys,

00:29:39.250 --> 00:29:44.630
and then you can also hit tab
should there be any linked content

00:29:44.680 --> 00:29:46.550
within the tabs themselves.

00:29:46.890 --> 00:29:53.020
Some of these tab modules,
widgets are marked up better

00:29:53.020 --> 00:29:56.980
on some page builders
than they are on others.

00:29:57.310 --> 00:30:01.320
I've taken this screenshot
and the following from a site

00:30:01.320 --> 00:30:03.320
that was built on Elementor.

00:30:03.950 --> 00:30:09.410
Then the one thing to also watch out
for is tabs on mobile.

00:30:09.410 --> 00:30:11.580
Whenever you get to a smaller screen,

00:30:11.620 --> 00:30:15.420
they have the tendency
just to want to squish together,

00:30:15.460 --> 00:30:18.500
making all that text very difficult
to read.

00:30:19.750 --> 00:30:23.210
That's why I really like
Elementor's approach.

00:30:24.300 --> 00:30:29.890
On this slide, I'm showing an example
of what the tabs look like on mobile.

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:39.310
They shrink down to an accordion-like view,
giving the user a more open layout,

00:30:39.310 --> 00:30:42.820
a larger target size,
and ensuring that

00:30:42.820 --> 00:30:47.410
none of those elements end up overlapping,

00:30:47.490 --> 00:30:50.780
just making it a little bit easier to use.

00:30:54.580 --> 00:30:55.160
All right.

00:30:55.500 --> 00:30:58.790
We're coming into our video section.

00:31:00.170 --> 00:31:05.670
Page builders love giving
their users different video options,

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:09.720
and one of the biggies is overlay images.

00:31:10.350 --> 00:31:15.640
These are images that you can put
on top of your video to fancy it up,

00:31:16.230 --> 00:31:19.100
but you have to watch out
with these kinds of features.

00:31:19.230 --> 00:31:22.400
Because though they may make
your video look a little bit nicer,

00:31:22.400 --> 00:31:24.280
they can serve as a keyboard trap.

00:31:25.280 --> 00:31:29.490
What ends up happening is that the user
is tabbing through your website,

00:31:29.860 --> 00:31:36.040
they get to the video and their focus
ends up going to the player controls

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:38.960
that are underneath that overlay image,

00:31:39.290 --> 00:31:42.840
so then the user has no clue
where they are on the website.

00:31:43.590 --> 00:31:45.670
It's frustrating, really.

00:31:47.340 --> 00:31:54.010
Then there's the autoplay option,
which should be purely avoided,

00:31:55.100 --> 00:31:59.850
that no user loves to show up on a site
and get bombarded with audio

00:31:59.850 --> 00:32:01.730
that they don't know
where it's coming from,

00:32:02.110 --> 00:32:04.980
or unexpected movement
or anything like that.

00:32:05.820 --> 00:32:08.490
Let them play the video for themselves.

00:32:08.950 --> 00:32:12.320
Then the other option is player controls.

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:15.330
For some reason, page builders offer this,

00:32:15.330 --> 00:32:19.790
where you can turn the player
controls off of a video.

00:32:20.160 --> 00:32:25.210
Things like the play button, volume,
seeking through the video,

00:32:25.210 --> 00:32:28.510
just let the users have it.

00:32:28.510 --> 00:32:31.510
Make these videos accessible for all.

00:32:33.220 --> 00:32:36.390
Here I have a screenshot
of the video options

00:32:36.390 --> 00:32:41.190
within an Elementor editor
with the autoplay,

00:32:41.770 --> 00:32:47.730
mute and loop all turned off,
and the player controls is set to on,

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:54.620
which is the ideal settings
that you are going for.

00:32:56.200 --> 00:33:01.120
Then here's a screenshot of what
an image overlay settings

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.250
might look like within your page builder.

00:33:03.250 --> 00:33:06.170
This one was taken from Elementor.

00:33:06.420 --> 00:33:12.220
We can see the image overlay section
with the image overlay set to on,

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:16.680
and then there's just a placeholder
in that area.

00:33:18.930 --> 00:33:23.980
Then the videos continue here
with background videos.

00:33:24.020 --> 00:33:28.190
Background videos are popular
for hero backgrounds,

00:33:28.570 --> 00:33:33.780
but that continuous movement
can be distressing for users.

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:39.200
I find that offering a clear
pause/play button for the user

00:33:39.200 --> 00:33:44.670
to be able to stop the video
should they wish is a good option.

00:33:44.670 --> 00:33:50.130
Unfortunately, I haven't found
a page builder that has this baked in,

00:33:50.130 --> 00:33:55.720
so I've always had to add some custom
code to do it myself, but it is possible.

00:33:56.260 --> 00:34:00.100
Any page-builder people listening out there,
please add this as an option.

00:34:00.140 --> 00:34:02.390
We would all love you very much.

00:34:03.600 --> 00:34:09.570
Then also ensuring that those background
videos have a good contrast for--

00:34:09.570 --> 00:34:14.030
if you're overlaying any text,
that adding a dark overlay

00:34:14.030 --> 00:34:16.320
can be a good solution for that.

00:34:18.320 --> 00:34:20.030
I just have a screenshot.

00:34:20.080 --> 00:34:24.790
Again, I wasn't going to subject you
to all the movement of a video,

00:34:24.870 --> 00:34:26.790
but in the screenshot,

00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:33.090
we can see that there is a little pause
button up in the upper right-hand corner.

00:34:33.380 --> 00:34:38.180
Then we have some white text
and there's a dark overlay,

00:34:38.260 --> 00:34:42.890
so the user can easily read the content.

00:34:45.890 --> 00:34:46.440
All right.

00:34:46.730 --> 00:34:49.650
Now we're getting into
a little bit of a biggie.

00:34:49.980 --> 00:34:53.610
It is our dynamic post filtering.

00:34:55.030 --> 00:35:01.700
A lot of page builders will offer
like category filtering for blog posts

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:03.330
and different things like that.

00:35:03.910 --> 00:35:08.630
Unfortunately,
these usually aren't marked up properly.

00:35:09.330 --> 00:35:11.380
Whenever the results are on the same page,

00:35:11.380 --> 00:35:15.380
they are often missing
those proper status messages,

00:35:16.930 --> 00:35:20.760
refocusing the user to where
they should be after the update,

00:35:21.100 --> 00:35:23.890
and including a proper submit button.

00:35:24.890 --> 00:35:29.100
This is a proceed with caution,
but definitely,

00:35:29.100 --> 00:35:34.940
with proper markup,
you can make it work for you.

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:42.200
Unfortunately, a lot of that proper markup
is going to be through some custom code.

00:35:43.790 --> 00:35:49.040
On the on screen here,
I have an example of some post filters

00:35:49.040 --> 00:35:52.130
that I pulled from
the Oxygen Builder website.

00:35:52.790 --> 00:35:55.710
We see some button filters on the left.

00:35:56.460 --> 00:35:59.260
Which button filters are great.

00:35:59.260 --> 00:36:00.720
You can select one.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:07.430
Then if the content changes,
we can serve the user a status message,

00:36:07.930 --> 00:36:09.850
so if they're on assistive technology,

00:36:09.850 --> 00:36:12.480
they know that something
on the page has changed.

00:36:12.980 --> 00:36:16.110
Then we update those blog posts.

00:36:16.320 --> 00:36:18.530
If, say, this were a dropdown,

00:36:18.610 --> 00:36:22.030
where the user has to select
an item from the dropdown,

00:36:22.410 --> 00:36:26.660
then we would want to ensure that
there's a nice apply button.

00:36:26.870 --> 00:36:31.790
That way, we're not changing
those results on an input.

00:36:32.670 --> 00:36:34.750
Just keeping a close eye on that.

00:36:36.090 --> 00:36:41.890
Then last but not least,
waving us in is our contact forms.

00:36:41.930 --> 00:36:47.220
A lot of page builders
have built-in contact forms that,

00:36:47.470 --> 00:36:51.770
unfortunately,
aren't marked up properly with proper labels,

00:36:51.900 --> 00:36:56.110
required field indication,
and proper validation messages.

00:36:57.190 --> 00:37:00.780
This is something that is a proceed
with caution.

00:37:00.780 --> 00:37:05.620
There's a lot of good third-party
plugins out there, such as Gravity Forms,

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:12.000
that offer you a little bit more flexibility
and better leverage over your forms.

00:37:13.670 --> 00:37:17.750
An example here,
I pulled this from the Divi website,

00:37:17.800 --> 00:37:20.260
is we have a contact form,

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:25.260
and they're using placeholders
instead of labels.

00:37:25.640 --> 00:37:30.230
If a user begins to type in there,
they won't remember what field they're on.

00:37:30.230 --> 00:37:32.190
It's problematic.

00:37:32.190 --> 00:37:33.770
It's hard to use.

00:37:34.850 --> 00:37:40.650
Then if they were to hit submit,
we see a screenshot

00:37:40.690 --> 00:37:45.320
of the submitted version
where there's validation errors.

00:37:48.030 --> 00:37:51.580
There's no required indication on these.

00:37:52.830 --> 00:37:56.130
It just says,
"Please fill in the following fields,"

00:37:56.130 --> 00:38:01.670
and lists name and message,
but there's still nothing telling you

00:38:01.670 --> 00:38:03.840
that these fields are required.

00:38:05.470 --> 00:38:07.890
We entered an invalid email address

00:38:07.890 --> 00:38:09.560
and it just says, "Invalid email,"

00:38:09.560 --> 00:38:15.520
but it doesn't give us any good reason
of why or how to fix it.

00:38:17.360 --> 00:38:19.690
I pulled another example here.

00:38:19.730 --> 00:38:26.410
We have a screenshot, and we can see
that we have the email labels

00:38:26.740 --> 00:38:29.490
with the required indicators on them.

00:38:29.530 --> 00:38:35.370
Then you have an invalid email address
typed in, just email@ex.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.130
We get a proper validation message
this time that says,

00:38:39.130 --> 00:38:41.090
"The email address entered is invalid.

00:38:41.090 --> 00:38:42.630
Please check the formatting,"

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:47.140
and then gives an example
of a proper email address.

00:38:47.180 --> 00:38:52.640
That is a better way to let users know that,
hey, you messed up.

00:38:54.730 --> 00:38:56.600
Here's how you can easily fix it.

00:38:58.650 --> 00:39:01.230
That leads us to our wrap-up.

00:39:02.570 --> 00:39:05.400
At the end of the day, page builders are-

00:39:05.450 --> 00:39:10.070
they can be super helpful
and these incredibly flexible tools,

00:39:10.070 --> 00:39:12.700
but they come with a lot of responsibility

00:39:12.990 --> 00:39:19.000
at not just blindly trusting
these page builders,

00:39:20.040 --> 00:39:24.010
and ensuring that we are doing all
the testing and everything as needed.

00:39:24.590 --> 00:39:30.220
Today I will not be giving you
what I think the best,

00:39:30.220 --> 00:39:32.970
most accessible page builder is,

00:39:33.390 --> 00:39:36.270
but if that is something
that you are curious in,

00:39:36.270 --> 00:39:40.310
there are lots of blog posts and podcasts.

00:39:40.940 --> 00:39:43.440
I know that there's some
that just recently happened

00:39:43.440 --> 00:39:47.110
that go over all that
and give a better look.

