00:40:14.100 --> 00:40:21.230
Rosita asks, "I have a problem
with the section tag in Elementor.

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:26.610
It converts all of the inner containers
into sections automatically.

00:40:27.900 --> 00:40:29.240
That is not correct, right?"

00:40:32.910 --> 00:40:33.450
<v Scarlett> Yes.

00:40:33.950 --> 00:40:38.040
Elementor now offers
a container structure as well.

00:40:38.040 --> 00:40:44.000
Their previous version, every one of those--
every section,

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:49.340
is literally what they call it,
did have the section tag on it.

00:40:49.920 --> 00:40:54.510
Now if you are switching over
to their new container structure,

00:40:54.550 --> 00:40:56.930
though it may look scary,
I do recommend it.

00:40:56.930 --> 00:41:01.480
It gives you a lot more flexibility
to be able to assign those landmarks,

00:41:01.690 --> 00:41:04.730
like I showed within that screenshot.

00:41:08.360 --> 00:41:09.150
<v Simon> Great.

00:41:09.150 --> 00:41:10.360
Thank you for that.

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:13.990
All right.

00:41:15.410 --> 00:41:21.410
David says that Elementor Pro's custom
attributes are added

00:41:21.460 --> 00:41:25.170
to the wrapper div
instead of the inner element.

00:41:29.340 --> 00:41:36.100
Is that a good way for remediating
accessibility issues?

00:41:38.390 --> 00:41:40.560
<v Scarlett> Not always.

00:41:41.060 --> 00:41:43.650
You will want to make sure
that wherever your--

00:41:44.100 --> 00:41:48.480
your custom attribute is being applied
to wherever it's needed.

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:52.610
For instance, in our primary nav example,

00:41:53.200 --> 00:41:58.790
you would want to make sure that
it is getting applied where that nav tag is.

00:41:58.790 --> 00:42:02.000
Unfortunately,
sometimes within page builders,

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:04.710
it's hard to tell exactly
where it's going to add it,

00:42:04.710 --> 00:42:08.340
and a lot of times it does end up
adding it to that wrapper.

00:42:10.460 --> 00:42:14.260
That's where adding some custom code
and things like that,

00:42:14.260 --> 00:42:17.010
unfortunately, come in.

00:42:17.640 --> 00:42:20.060
Ultimately,
I would say just do your testing

00:42:20.060 --> 00:42:22.310
and make sure that it makes sense
where it's at.

00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:26.560
<v Simon> All right, thank you.

00:42:28.980 --> 00:42:34.030
Someone mentions that sliders are the one

00:42:34.030 --> 00:42:38.120
and only for everyone
in the world of websites.

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:45.080
I've got my clients to not do it,
use sliders, I guess,

00:42:45.080 --> 00:42:47.500
but what alternatives do you use?

00:42:47.830 --> 00:42:51.250
Can you explain or give a URL,

00:42:51.250 --> 00:42:54.170
an example about
how to make a slider accessible?

00:42:56.760 --> 00:42:57.300
<v Scarlett> Yes.

00:42:58.850 --> 00:43:02.970
My recommendation is just don't.

00:43:03.020 --> 00:43:07.150
I know that that's not the most popular
answer for some clients.

00:43:07.150 --> 00:43:09.400
I know that some really like it.

00:43:09.810 --> 00:43:12.230
If you can provide them a good argument--

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:15.950
I know a lot like sliders
within the heroes.

00:43:17.860 --> 00:43:21.530
If you can compromise on having
a background image

00:43:21.530 --> 00:43:23.540
with maybe some overlaid text,

00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:27.830
ensuring that there's a nice background
overlay for that high contrast.

00:43:28.370 --> 00:43:33.920
Then I usually recommend
an image-text section,

00:43:33.920 --> 00:43:36.380
so something that has an image
and some text,

00:43:36.800 --> 00:43:41.390
just so that way the user can see
everything laid out for them.

00:43:42.010 --> 00:43:43.640
I think the argument here is really,

00:43:43.810 --> 00:43:47.100
don't be hiding this content
from your users.

00:43:47.100 --> 00:43:50.150
It can really affect
a company's bottom line,

00:43:50.150 --> 00:43:52.190
if you happen to be building
for a company,

00:43:52.570 --> 00:43:56.150
that users are missing out on
a lot of things or getting frustrated.

00:43:56.400 --> 00:43:58.360
Oh, and for an accessible slider,

00:43:58.360 --> 00:44:03.120
I know that the W3C does have examples

00:44:03.120 --> 00:44:06.750
of what an accessible slider markup
looks like as well.

00:44:07.750 --> 00:44:07.960
<v Simon> Yes.

00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:12.670
Just to confirm, you're talking about
slider carousels for images

00:44:12.670 --> 00:44:13.750
and other content, right?

00:44:13.750 --> 00:44:17.380
Not just form control sliders
that are custom components, correct?

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:18.470
<v Scarlett> Correct, yes.

00:44:18.510 --> 00:44:19.630
Thank you, Simon.

00:44:19.630 --> 00:44:19.930
Yes.

00:44:20.220 --> 00:44:20.840
<v Simon> Sure, yes.

